{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519721"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:15:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:15:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13065"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13065"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.07,0.06,0.76,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5502"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76429"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5502"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13065"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61926"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1944"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9361"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9791"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76429"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of progressive weakness. The weakness initially started in his right hand, causing difficulty writing and buttoning shirts. The weakness has spread to his right arm and shoulder, and he has begun to notice mild weakness in his left hand. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His right hand has atrophied, with significant wasting of the thenar eminence. His power is reduced in his right arm, most prominently distally. He has bilateral spasticity and hyperreflexia in his upper limbs. The coordination of his right arm is impaired. Vibration and proprioception are intact bilaterally. His lower limb examination is unremarkable. His cranial nerve examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiple sclerosis","Myasthenia gravis","Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome","Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis","Parkinson disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Eamyotrophic lateral sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E. The combination of upper motor neuron signs (spasticity, hyperreflexia) and lower motor neuron signs (muscle wasting, weakness) is pathognomonic. The focal onset in one limb with contiguous spread is also typical. The absence of sensory symptoms and preserved proprioception help distinguish it from other conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGuillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with an acute ascending paralysis over days to weeks, with areflexia and sensory symptoms. The chronicity and presence of upper motor neuron signs make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E characteristically presents with episodes of neurological dysfunction separated in time and space. While it can cause upper motor neuron signs, it does not cause muscle wasting. The absence of sensory symptoms or visual disturbance makes this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyasthenia gravis\u003C/strong\u003E causes fatigable weakness that typically affects ocular and bulbar muscles early. The presence of muscle wasting and upper motor neuron signs excludes this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParkinson disease\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by bradykinesia, rigidity, tremor, and postural instability. It does not cause muscle wasting or hyperreflexia, and symptoms are typically bilateral though asymmetric.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis presents with progressive weakness and mixed upper and lower motor neuron signs.","The combination of muscle wasting (lower motor neuron sign) with hyperreflexia and spasticity (upper motor neuron signs) is characteristic of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis.","Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis typically begins focally and spreads contiguously, often starting in one limb."],"references":["Brown RH, Al-Chalabi A. Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis. N Engl J Med. 2017 Jul 13;377(2):162-172. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMra1603471"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61926"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13065"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61926"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T13:57:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T13:57:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5502"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76429"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes"